Worth a visit if you love Joan Miro and its legacy!

Nice little square, it has play areas for children. Former Blomet square, renamed in 2010, this green space was created the location of studios occupied by many artists, including Alfred Boucher, Pablo Emilio Gargallo, Andr√© Masson, Joan Mir√≥ and Robert Desnos. It owes its name to the bronze sculpture The Lunar Bird (1966) by Joan Mir√≥ (1893-1983), offered to the City of Paris by the artist. This square is equipped with bowling greens and ping pong tables. There is a play area for toddlers.

An emblematic place in Parisian literary and artistic history, the square de l'Oiseau Lunaire is now taken over by childhood, which tries to continue to bring a sweet mischief into the air.  Without any real aesthetic interest - apart from the statue of Jean Arp in the center of the Park, the explanatory cartel and its mystique are worth the little detour.  Very nice play area for children, by the way.
A quiet, peaceful, cozy place. Incredible trees, flowers. The playground, like all in Paris, brings a lot of pleasure to children. There is a tennis table and a foosball table. But bring your ball.
The Square Oiseau Lunaire offers children good places to play and have fun with each other. The park is very clean and maintained.
Small park ideal with young children, sandbox and games. Big advantage: only one entrance, making it easier to monitor toddlers remotely. Well attended.
Very good square, I daughter loves it.
Square with very nice games for children but which deserves to be a little better maintained.
A relaxing place sheltered from the tumult of Paris. I recommend reading, strolling, breathing...

Children are kings in this place which offers several activities! One downside concerns the very large sandbox (which is also very good) which a few days ago was filled with leaves and particularly buried and therefore damp... very unpleasant for young and old to make p√¢t√©s or more!

Very nice square when there is no work. You can have lunch there alone or with others without worry, when the sun is out, it's very pleasant. There are also shaded areas and public toilets. At lunchtime, there are very often groups of children playing ball... So be careful of your location üòÅ ‚Ä¶
Rather quiet square. Presence of games for children, ping pong table and table football.
A small square, rue Blomet. It takes its new name (it was formerly Blomet Square) from a strange and amusing statue of Juan Miro, the lunar bird, which is located there.
Large, very pleasant space with sandbox
Small park away from the street, children really like the play area for older children! Quite little known so quiet.

Open park for young and old, It has a child's structure in which there is a spider web in the middle.  Numerous benches are available to everyone and the park offers places on the grass, shaded, semi-shaded and sunny places.  I recommend this place even more because there are many restaurants nearby and the park is rather large compared to the place.
Small friendly square, shaded sandbox, recent wooden play structures, table football and ping-pong table. Everything you need for children aged 0 to 10 to have fun.

Very well maintained, well shaded and well equipped. It's a shame that it closes so early in winter and that the table football has not been repaired, it would just be necessary to reattach the players.

Small neighborhood square where local children meet after school. A nice playground for those over 5 years old, a sandbox, ping ping tables and some games for toddlers. Quite a few benches but no green space to sit on the grass.
Rare! A nice little park where children can play in complete safety from car traffic.
Small with lots of sand. Very little play and dirty appearance!! Strong point, the grass is very green and very pleasant for walking barefoot. I admit that I don't like it.
Without much interest but relatively calm. Children's games don't seem so bad. The sculpture is also used as such.
Convenient after school but there are few places and it is very hot in the summer (not very shaded)
The square is quiet and has play structures for children, there are small lawns for having lunch.
In the heart of Paris and between two buildings, this small park is the meeting place for snackers. There are also games for children and large trees for picnics underfoot üòä ‚Ä¶
Square very popular with children A sandbox. Games. A kind of castle. I recommend I just would have liked an extra patch of lawn
Nice park quite large with games for children, ping pong tables and table football as well as a large sandbox

Quiet but dirty... Seen when it opened at 9 a.m. a person was going to clean and collect the rubbish of poorly behaved people who do not use the trash cans available to them... Beautiful play structure redone for children from 5 years... but lots of pigeon shit on it.... Lots of benches, a sandbox, and a slide from 3 years old.

Small space but nice two play structures depending on the age of the child and a very nice low sand corner but smaller than before it's a big negative point and the games for little ones are really ridiculous compared to to that before damage

Square erected on the site of artists' studios including that of Juan Miro who lived there, to redeem itself from its concreteization and the destruction of these romantic workshops and courtyards the town hall had a statue placed in the middle of this place by Miro. without further comments....
Green enclave whose entrance is rue Blomet, with access to clean public toilets! Of course the Miro sculpture which is the eponym of this place!!!
